         <div type="translation">
            <p><choice corresp="#a1"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">Even about (something good) done (in secret) one should feel relieved. [31c] <hi>Sanskrit</hi> </seg></seg><seg><seg type="prim_transl">(Wenn es [scil. das Verdienst, Skt. puṇya] lange getan und auch wenn es in der Ferne) getan worden ist, dürfte er guten Mutes sein.</seg><seg type="sec_transl" resp="TI">(If it [i.e. the meritorious deed, Skt. puṇya] was done long and even if it) was done (far away), he should be of good cheer.</seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:schmidtkt1974"/><citedRange>175</citedRange></bibl></seg></choice><choice corresp="#a2"><seg><seg type="prim_transl"><hi>Sanskrit</hi> When a bad thing has been done, however, one feels sorrowful. [32a] <hi>Sanskrit</hi></seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#a3"><seg><seg type="prim_transl"><hi>Sanskrit</hi> and when it has been done in secret (one feels sorrowful). [32c]</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#a4"><seg><seg type="prim_transl"><hi>Sanskrit</hi> But when a good deed (has been done one rejoices). [33a]</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#a5"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">Even when it has been done in the past, (even) if it has been done far away, one rejoices. [33b] </seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b2"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">This one feels sorrowful indeed, this one feels very sorrowful. [34c]</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b3"><seg><seg type="prim_transl"><hi>Sanskrit</hi> Here one rejoices ..., [35a]</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b4"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">having done a good deed one rejoices on both sides (= in this life and in afterlife). [35b]</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b5"><seg><seg type="prim_transl"><hi>Sanskrit</hi> having seen the pure deed (done by himself). [35d] </seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b6"><seg><seg type="prim_transl"><hi>Sanskrit</hi> (Even when it has been done) in the past ... [36b]</seg></seg></choice></p>
         </div>
         <div type="comments">
            <p><note type="lingcomment">Note that several forms of the text point to archaic Tocharian B: <hi>yärpone</hi> (a4), <hi>olyäpotse</hi> (b2), <hi>lyelyäkormeṃ</hi> (b5) and <hi>laukä(ññe)</hi> (b6).</note><note type="parallels">Sanskrit (<bibl><title corresp="ref:bernhard1965"/><citedRange>362-364</citedRange></bibl>)</note><note corresp="#a1" type="philcomment">The first word ought to be restored as <hi>yāmoṣne</hi> translating Skt. <hi>kṛte</hi> (31c).</note><note corresp="#a2" type="philcomment">Before the tear of the paper there is place for four akṣaras that are largely erased; one can nevertheless read the beginning of the Sanskrit pāda 32b.</note><note corresp="#a3" type="philcomment">Before the tear of the paper one finds the schnurloch and maybe two erased akṣaras.</note><note corresp="#a5" type="philcomment">The first word ought to be restored as <hi>yāmoṣne</hi> translating Skt. <hi>kṛte</hi> (33b).</note><note corresp="#a6" type="philcomment">and <ref type="ms" target="#b1"/> contain no more than unreadable remains of some akṣaras.</note><note corresp="#b3" type="philcomment">Skt. <hi>pretya</hi> has been misspelled as <hi>pratya</hi> and the verb Skt. <hi>nandati</hi> as <hi>ndate</hi>.</note><note corresp="#b4" type="lingcomment">At the beginning of the line one reads very clearly <hi>yärpo</hi> instead of <hi>yarpo</hi>. But it is due to the fact that it belongs to a compound translating Skt. <hi>kṛtapuṇyaḥ</hi> (35b). Probably this compound can be restored as <hi>yamor-yärpo</hi>.</note><note corresp="#b4" type="philcomment">After the dot there is space for 3-4 akṣaras of Sanskrit text (35c).</note><note corresp="#b5" type="lingcomment">As match of Skt. <hi>viśuddham</hi> lit. ‘clean, pure’ (35d) the obvious restoration is the TB adjective <hi>astare</hi>.</note><note corresp="#b5" type="philcomment">The spelling <hi>atmana</hi> is mistaken for Skt. <hi>ātmanaḥ</hi> (35d). The preceding word was <hi>viśuddham</hi>. After the initial vowel <hi>a</hi> some akṣaras are erased before the tear of the paper.</note><note corresp="#b6" type="lingcomment">Apparently, in order to translate Skt. <hi>cira-</hi> ‘lasting a long time, existing from ancient time’ Tocharian used an adjective derived from the same basis as TB <hi>lauke</hi> ‘distant, remote’, which in this text corresponds to Skt. <hi>dūra-</hi> ‘being far away’. It seems possible to restore the former adjective as an archaic form <hi>laukäññe</hi> of classical <hi>laukaññe</hi>.</note></p>
